Yes, a simple Forth stack, as well as a minimal Forth interpreter, can indeed be implemented in C. The stack is a fundamental element in Forth for parameter passing between operations (known as "words" in Forth parlance). In C, you can use an array to represent the stack and use a stack pointer or index to manage the stack elements. Here's a basic example of how you might implement a stack suitable for Forth in C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

#define STACK_SIZE 256 // Define the maximum size of the stack

// Declare the stack and the stack pointer
int stack[STACK_SIZE];
int sp = 0; // Stack pointer, points to the next free stack slot

// Push a value onto the stack
void push(int value) {
    if (sp < STACK_SIZE) {
        stack[sp++] = value;
    } else {
        fprintf(stderr, "Stack overflow\n");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }
}

// Pop a value from the stack
int pop() {
    if (sp > 0) {
        return stack[--sp];
    } else {
        fprintf(stderr, "Stack underflow\n");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }
}

// Peek at the top value of the stack without popping
int top() {
    if (sp > 0) {
        return stack[sp - 1];
    } else {
        fprintf(stderr, "Stack is empty\n");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }
}

int main() {
    push(10);
    push(20);
    int a = pop();
    int b = pop();
    printf("Popped values: %d and %d\n", a, b);

    // Example usage with underflow check
    if (sp > 0) {
        int c = pop();
        printf("Popped value: %d\n", c);
    } else {
        printf("Cannot pop, stack is empty\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code demonstrates a simple stack that can be integrated into a Forth interpreter. However, a complete Forth system would require additional components such as a dictionary for word definitions, a lexer for tokenizing input, an inner interpreter to execute the words, and more.

Additionally, C is often used to implement the core of more complex Forth systems due to its low-level capabilities and efficiency. This allows for the creation of performant and portable Forth environments that can run on a variety of hardware platforms.
